===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|𠨍|皀|ls=ic|t1=two people facing each other|t2=a round-mouthed food vessel}} – to feast; the original script of {{och-l|饗}}. The sense "village" was a result of phonetic borrowing or semantic shifting.

In early writing, the character was virtually indistinguishable from {{och-l|卿}}. Semantically, {{och-l|卿|gloss=elder; leader}} and {{och-l|鄉|gloss=community; district; village}}, likely cognates too, were both represented by the event depicted in the ideogram – {{och-l|饗|gloss=ritual feasting}}, which was central to the community life ({{zh-ref|Yang, 1965}}).

The right half is unrelated to {{zh-l|*郎}}, as {{zh-l|*良}} in {{lang|zh|鄉}} was derived from {{zh-l|*皀}} during the formation of the [[clerical script]].

